1. Our Relationships with Other People


What kind of people live in today’s world?

Answer:

2 Timothy 3:1-3

"3 But know this, that in the last days critical times hard to deal with will be here. 2 For men will be lovers of themselves, lovers of money, boastful, haughty, blasphemers, disobedient to parents, unthankful, disloyal, 3 having no natural affection, not open to any agreement, slanderers, without self-control, fierce, without love of goodness."

Do those conditions sound familiar to you today?

Turn on the news, what do you see?

    • Globally:  Wars; countries fight each other over disagreements.
    • Countries divided: Nations face problems internally; cultural, political, racial.
    • Family setting: Families face daily challenges trying to stay united.
    • Self-centered attitudes: Many suffer because of thoughtless, selfish people.

How do we address the root cause of these issues?

The Bible had the insight to predict the problem, can it also give us the answer?

Bible principle: Matthew chapter 7:12. Jesus’ advice:
“All things, therefore, that you want men to do to you, you also must do to them. This, in fact, is what the Law and the Prophets mean.”
Treat others how you want to be treated.
That principle is simple.
But it’s powerful.

Think about the contrast.
At 2 Timothy 3, we read earlier about people who are lovers of themselves.
But Jesus here teaches us to think about others.

So when we apply this principle, we ask:
“How would I want to be treated if I were in their situation?”

Would I appreciate patience? Kindness?
Would I appreciate someone giving me the benefit of the doubt?
Would I appreciate help before I had to ask?
Of course we would.

So in everyday life, this principle moves us to act.
Maybe someone seems discouraged.
We offer encouragement.
Maybe someone makes a mistake.
We show patience.
Maybe someone needs help.
We offer before they have to ask.

It’s like holding a door open for someone whose hands are full.
It’s not complicated.
It may only take a moment.
But to the person carrying the load, it can mean a lot.

So can this Bible principle help us deal better with other people?
Yes.
Because in a world where many are becoming “lovers of themselves,” Jesus teaches us how to show love to others.


(pause)

Of course, we know that as imperfect humans, we make mistakes.  Our relationships with other people aren’t perfect.

We might say or do something that creates a problem with someone else.

What should we do when that happens?

Matthew 5:23-25:

“If, then, you are bringing your gift to the altar and there you remember that your brother has something against you, 24 leave your gift there in front of the altar, and go away. First make your peace with your brother, and then come back and offer your gift.”

Making peace.  Being forgiving.

Is that easy?

As the verse shows, it requires effort.  Self sacrifice.

What's the benefit?

By quickly seeking to make peace with others:

    • We have the opportunity to repair our relationship with them.
    • We can enjoy a good conscience knowing that we've done all we can to make things right.

A Real-Life Example:

    • Rukia was an Albanian woman in her 60s.
        ◦ Because of a family disagreement, she didn't speak to a family member for over 17 years.
        ◦ She began studying the Bible with Jehovah’s Witnesses and learned that true Christians have to be at peace with others, not holding grudges.

    • What did she do?
        ◦ She prayed all night.
        ◦ Walked to her brother's home; family was shocked that she was there.
        ◦ Rukia asked to see her brother and calmly explained that learning about Bible principles and about Jehovah had motivated her to make peace with her brother.

    • The outcome:
        ◦ After tears and hugs, they celebrated a special reunion.

    • The Lesson:
        ◦ By applying Bible principles, she was able to restore her relationship with her brother and bring peace to her family.

Quick recap:
What did we learn from these two Bible principles?
Matthew 7:12 helps us ask:
“How would I want to be treated?”
Matthew 5:23, 24 helps us ask:
“What can I do to restore peace?”
So can Bible principles help us deal with difficult people and strained relationships?
Yes.
They help us become more thoughtful, more forgiving, and more willing to take the initiative.
(pause)

That’s one everyday problem where Bible principles can help us cope.

