Can Bible principles help with that too?

2. Can Bible Principles Help Us Find Real Happiness?

It goes without saying that we all want to be happy.
But where does the world often tell us to look for happiness?
    • Material things
    • Prominence
    • Personal achievement
    • Comfort
    • Entertainment
    • Being admired by others

And to be fair, those things may give a measure of enjoyment.
But they don’t always lead to lasting happiness.
Many people live with an “I’ll be happy when...” attitude.
    • I’ll be happy when I get my dream job
    • I’ll be happy when I own my own home
    • I’ll be happy when I get married
    • I’ll be happy when I have children
    • I’ll be happy when the children leave home

(pause)(smile)

The problem is, the finish line keeps moving.
Reaching a goal can make us happy.
But that kind of happiness is not always guaranteed.
And even when it comes, it can fade.

Jesus gave this warning.  He told his followers:

“Even when a person has an abundance, his life does not result from the things he possesses.”

(Luke 12:15)

Lasting happiness isn't based solely on our achievements or the things we own.

What is it based on?

Evidence suggests that some things are more consistently associated with happiness:

        ◦ Having contentment
        ◦ Being generous
        ◦ Showing love for others

Interestingly, all three of those ideas can be summed up in one Bible Principle:

Acts 20:35:

“There is more happiness in giving than there is in receiving.”

So what contributes to real happiness?

One way, is by being generous.

What can we give?
    • Material things
    • Time
    • Energy
    • Attention
    • Encouragement
    • Practical help

This is especially appreciated in the family.
    • Parents can give time to their children
    • Husbands and wives can give attention to each other
    • Friends can give encouragement
    • Congregation members can give support
    • Most importantly, we can give of our time in helping others to learn about Jehovah and the beautiful hope that the Bible provides for the future.

A Real-Life Example

Tom, a builder living in Hawaii, volunteered to help build places of worship on Pacific islands where people have little materially.

Tom noticed something about these humble people. He said: “My Christian brothers and sisters in these islands were truly happy. They helped me see more clearly that money and possessions are not the secret to happiness.”

He also observed the volunteers who worked with him in the islands and noticed how contented they were. “They could have made a lot of money,” said Tom. “But they chose to keep spiritual things in first place and maintain a simple life-style.”
Moved by these examples, Tom simplified his own life so that he could devote more time to his family and to spiritual pursuits​—a move, it says, that he has never regretted.

Recap:  What will help us find true happiness?

Bible Principles:

1. Lasting happiness isn't based solely on our achievements or the things we own (Luke 12:15)
2. There is more happiness in giving (Acts 20:35)
3. Happy are those conscious of their spiritual need (Matthew 5:3)

So can Bible principles help us find real happiness?

Yes.

They help us see that lasting happiness is not based on constantly receiving more.

Often, it comes from giving more.

(pause)

But that raises another everyday problem.

If happiness doesn’t come from constantly getting more, how can we stay balanced in a world that keeps telling us we need more?

In the experience we just discussed, did you notice that Tom simplified his life?

That leads us to another area where Bible principles can help us cope:

Material pressure.

The world around us doesn't encourage a simple life.

In fact, just the opposite.  We're pressured to...

    • Study more
    • Work more
    • Buy more
    • Accomplish more
    • Upgrade more
    • Compare more

We're in an environment that constantly has us thinking about material things.

And to be honest, even just living within our means can be a challenge.
Basic needs take time, energy, and money.
But even if we have good intentions, if we are not careful, material concerns could become our main focus.

3. Can Bible Principles Help Us Stay Balanced Under Material Pressure?

1 Timothy 6:6-8:

“To be sure, there is great gain in godly devotion along with contentment. For we have brought nothing into the world, and neither can we carry anything out. So, having food and clothing, we will be content with these things.”

What's the standard of living it mentions?

    • Food and clothing.
    • Talking about basic needs.
            ▪ Being content with what is necessary

Why is contentment so important?

Imagine you need to fill a bucket with water.
But the bucket is full of holes.
What will happen?
    • No matter how much water you pour in, it keeps leaking out.
    • You can pour faster.
    • You can pour more.
    • But the bucket still ends up empty.

So what do you need to do?
You need to patch the holes.
In a similar way, trying to find satisfaction by constantly getting more is like trying to fill a leaking bucket.
The issue is not always how much we have.
Sometimes the issue is that something keeps draining away our satisfaction.
Contentment patches the holes.
It helps us appreciate what we already have.
It helps us stop wasting our energy chasing things that will never fully satisfy us.

So realistically, how can we be content?  What does contentment really mean?

Contentment does not mean:
    • Ignoring financial responsibilities
    • Refusing to work hard
    • Pretending life is easy
    • Saying basic needs don’t matter
But if we are content, we will avoid:
    • Constantly comparing ourselves to others
    • Using all our time to pursue things we don’t really need
    • Taking on unnecessary debt
    • Focusing too much on work
    • Making risky financial decisions just to get ahead

If we notice ourselves becoming consumed by what we lack, what can help?
    • Shift our focus to what we already have
    • Reflect on our blessings
    • Keep spiritual things first
    • Remember what Jehovah says is truly valuable

Recap

It can be a challenge to take care of ourselves financially.

The world pushes us to put more and more time and energy into having more.

But Bible principles help us:
    • Deal with economic pressure
    • Manage work and finances in a balanced way
    • Keep life simple
    • Be content with what we have — 1 Timothy 6:8

(pause)

So can Bible principles help us stay balanced when facing material pressure?

Yes.

They help us be content, keep life simple, and avoid being controlled by the constant desire for more.

But of course, even when we try to live simply, we still face problems.

Bills come.

Health changes.

Family problems appear.

The future can feel uncertain.

And when those things build up, they can create another problem we all have to deal with:

Anxiety.

4. Can Bible Principles Help Us Cope With Anxiety?

As Christians, we aren’t surprised by the anxieties of life.
Earlier we read that these are “critical times hard to deal with.”
And today we’ve already talked about several things that can cause anxiety:
    • Problems with people
    • Family conflict
    • Financial pressure
    • The pressure to keep up
    • Uncertainty about the future

Knowing why the world is this way helps us.
But it does not automatically remove anxiety.
So what can we do when anxiety weighs us down?

Bible principle:

Philippians 4:6-7:

“Do not be anxious over anything, but in everything by prayer and supplication along with thanksgiving, let your petitions be made known to God; and the peace of God that surpasses all understanding will guard your hearts and your mental powers by means of Christ Jesus.”

What can we do when something starts to make us anxious?

Step 1: Pray
Approach Jehovah in earnest prayer
Tell him what we are feeling
Be specific when we can
Ask for help, wisdom, strength, and peace

The result?

The peace of God can guard our hearts and mental powers.

Jehovah may not remove the problem immediately.

But he can guard what the problem is trying to damage:

our heart
our thinking
our trust in him

Step 2: Act in Harmony With Our Prayers

We should not just leave it there.

Many anxieties can be avoided or minimized if we act in harmony with our prayers.

We do what we reasonably can.

If there is a problem, we try to address it
If we need help, we ask for help
If we need to make a decision, we look for Bible principles
If we need support, we draw close to the congregation
If we need to change something, we take practical steps

Prayer is not an excuse to do nothing.

Prayer helps us do what we can while trusting Jehovah with what we cannot control.

Step 3: Trust Jehovah’s Timing

Jehovah does not always answer prayers in the way we expect.

And he may not answer as quickly as we would like.

We may want immediate relief.

But Jehovah knows exactly how and when to help us.

And as the verse says, his peace “surpasses all understanding.”

That means Jehovah can give us calm even when the situation itself has not fully changed.


Let’s talk about one last brief experience:

The experience is of one of our Christian friends named Barbara, who was going through a difficult time a few years ago.  She said:

    • “My job, family, friends—nothing seemed to be working out. I didn’t know what to do.”
    • Barbara instinctively prayed for help, but there was a problem—“I didn’t know what to ask Jehovah for”.
    • Finally, she asked for peace of mind and prayed each night that Jehovah would help her not to worry about everything.
    • How did that prayer help her?
    • Barbara says: “A few days later, I realized that although my problems hadn’t disappeared, I wasn’t so occupied or concerned with them anymore.”

Friends, at times, we all have anxieties that we have to deal with.

So can Bible principles help us cope with anxiety?

Yes.

They teach us to pray to Jehovah, act in harmony with our prayers, and trust him to give us peace.

Philippians 4:6, 7 shows that Jehovah can guard our heart, our thinking, and our trust in him.

